<subSubSection pageNumber="658" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="658">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="658">Note:</emphasis>
Applequist (in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="658">Taxon</emphasis>
51: 757-761. 2003) gives a detailed review of the nomenclatural complexities associated with this name, and accepts 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Griersonâ€™s">Grierson's</normalizedToken>
type choice (a specimen of chamomile). Although both 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Matricaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="chamomilla">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="658">M. chamomilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="L." authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Matricaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="recutita">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="658">M. recutita</emphasis>
L.
</taxonomicName>
(which has also been used for the species) date from 1753, Applequist argues that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Matricaria" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="chamomilla">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="658">M. chamomilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the correct name, Visiani having been the first to combine the two in 1844.
</paragraph>
